            <h4>Orthodox MMA Trainer - Final Year Thesis</h4>
            <br>
            <p>For my final year thesis, my project partner and I created a progressive web application which utilised pose estimation and computer vision to predict a user's technique / form in regards to certain strikes used within mixed martial arts, such as a jab.</p>

            <p>We created datasets by recording poor and proper technique, reducing the dimensionality of the data and then feeding this data to <a href="https://google.github.io/mediapipe/solutions/pose.html">BlazePose.</a> This is a pose estimation pipeline which was cutting edge at the time. It produces pose estimations, frame-by-frame, in the form of 32 pose landmarks. This data was then used to create datasets and train multiple classifiers. The resulting dataset is available <a href="https://www.kaggle.com/billohanlon/jab-technique-prediction-with-body-landmark-data">here.</a></p>

            <p>The web application was written using Flask, Python, Javascript (used for video encoding), HTML and CSS, and was hosted on an AWS EC2 instance. GoLang was also used to produce an API for storing feedback reports produced by users and user authentification.</p>

            <img src="static/sys_arch.JPG" alt="" class="graph-image">

            <p>For more detail, along with a user guide and technical specification please refer to the <a href="https://github.com/billoh28/OrthodoxMMA">Project Github Repository</a></p>
            <p>The web application is available through the following link: <a href="https://orthodoxmma.com/">Orthodox MMA</a></p>
